he following starter code to write the solution to the problem and enclose your code within delimiters.\n```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxValue(self, n: str, x: int) -> str:\n        \n```\n\n### Answer: (use the provided format with backticks)\n", "response": "```python\nclass Solution:\n    def maxValue(self, n: str, x: int) -> str:\n        if n[0] == '-':\n            # For negative numbers, we want to minimize the absolute value\n            for i in range(1, len(n)):\n                if int(n[i]) > x:\n                    return n[:i] + str(x) + n[i:]\n            return n + str(x)\n        else:\n            # For positive numbers, we want to maximize the value\n            for i in range(len(n)):\n                if int(n[i]) < x:\n                    return n[:i] + str(x) + n[i:]\n            return n + str(x)\n```\n\nThis solution handles both positive and negative numbers by iterating through the string representation of `n` and finding the appropriate position to insert `x` to achieve the maximum value. For negative numbers, it inserts `x` where it would make the number less negative (i.e., closer to zero), and for positive numbers, it inserts `x` where it would increase the value the most. If no such position is found, `x` is appended to the end of `n`.", "estimated_date": 1622332800000}